    <p><strong>Shock waves</strong> are sharp transitions in fluid or plasma where pressure, density, and velocity change abruptly. They occur when a flow exceeds the local signal speed and compresses the medium, converting bulk kinetic energy into heat and non-thermal particle energy.</p>

    <h2 id="background">Background</h2>
    <p>Shocks are ubiquitous in astrophysics: supernova remnants, jets, and colliding winds all host shocks. Rankine–Hugoniot relations describe the jump conditions across a shock for mass, momentum, and energy conservation.</p>

    <h2 id="physical-description">Physical description</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Compression</strong> — Density increases by the compression ratio set by upstream Mach number.</li>
      <li><strong>Heating</strong> — Bulk kinetic energy is converted into thermal energy and, in many cases, non-thermal particles.</li>
      <li><strong>Obliquity</strong> — The angle between shock normal and magnetic field affects particle reflection and acceleration efficiency.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="why-matters">Why this matters</h2>
    <p>Shocks provide sites for particle acceleration via Diffusive Shock Acceleration (DSA). In jets, standing shocks such as recollimation shocks can remain quasi-stationary and continually accelerate particles, feeding high-energy emission from jets and their cocoons. See [[diffusive-shock-acceleration]] and [[recollimation-shocks]].</p>

    <h2 id="observational-evidence">Observational evidence</h2>
    <p>Knots and hot spots in jet images, radio synchrotron spectra with power-law indices, and resolved X-ray emission all point to shock-accelerated non-thermal particles in jets.</p>

    <h2 id="references">Key references</h2>
